tcs-blacklist-table colgroup col.tcs-blacklist-col-logo{ display:none; }\n      .tcs-blacklist-table th:first-child,\n      .tcs-blacklist-table td:first-child{ display:none; }\n\n      /* Make Evidence button sit comfortably */\n      .tcs-blacklist-evidence-cell{\n        text-align:left;\n        padding-top: 8px;\n        padding-bottom: 12px;\n      }\n      .tcs-blacklist-evidence-cell a.tcs-btn{\n        width: 100%;\n        justify-content:center;\n      }\n    }\n  </style>\n\n  <div class=\"tcs-label-pill\" style=\"margin-bottom:12px;\">Online casino blacklist (verified entries)</div>\n\n  <p class=\"tcs-blacklist-help\">\n    This is TopCasinoScout\u2019s <strong>online casino blacklist</strong> (also referred to as our <strong>casino blacklist</strong>): a single, evidence-led table of operators we recommend you avoid.\n    Each entry highlights the specific risk signals we verified, so you can scan quickly and then open the full investigation when you need the supporting detail.\n  </p>\n\n  <div class=\"tcs-blacklist-legend\">\n    <div class=\"tcs-blacklist-chip\">\n      <b>Risk</b>\n      <p>Our severity call based on licensing clarity, payout reliability, and repeated complaint signals.</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"tcs-blacklist-chip\">\n      <b>TCS Score</b>\n      <p>Out of 10,000. A <strong>0 score</strong> indicates non-negotiable failures (for example, unverified licensing or severe payout risk).</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"tcs-blacklist-chip\">\n      <b>Evidence</b>\n      <p>Opens the full review with screenshots, terms audit notes, and the exact triggers behind the blacklist decision.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <table class=\"tcs-blacklist-table\" aria-label=\"Online casino blacklist table\">\n    <colgroup>\n      <col class=\"tcs-blacklist-col-logo\" style=\"width:10%;\">\n      <col style=\"width:18%;\">\n      <col style=\"width:10%;\">\n      <col style=\"width:12%;\">\n      <col style=\"width:26%;\">\n      <col style=\"width:16%;\">\n      <col style=\"width:8%;\">\n    </colgroup>\n\n    <thead>\n      <tr>\n        <th class=\"tcs-blacklist-col-logo\">Logo<span class=\"tcs-th-sub\">Brand mark</span></th>\n        <th>Casino<span class=\"tcs-th-sub\">Name + status</span></th>\n        <th>Risk<span class=\"tcs-th-sub\">High / Severe</span></th>\n        <th>TCS Score<span class=\"tcs-th-sub\">0\u201310,000</span></th>\n        <th>Primary issues<span class=\"tcs-th-sub\">What we verified</span></th>\n        <th>Evidence tags<span class=\"tcs-th-sub\">Fast scan labels</span></th>\n        <th>Evidence<span class=\"tcs-th-sub\">Full review</span></th>\n      </tr>\n    </thead>\n\n    <tbody>\n      <!-- CazinoStars -->\n      <tr>\n        <td class=\"tcs-blacklist-col-logo\">\n          <img\n            src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/cazino_stars_192.webp\"\n            alt=\"CazinoStars logo\"\n            class=\"tcs-blacklist-logo\"\n            loading=\"lazy\">\n        </td>\n\n        <td>\n          <strong style=\"color:#ffdd55;\">CazinoStars</strong><br>\n          <span class=\"tcs-tagline\">Blacklisted \u2022 Avoid depositing</span>\n        </td>\n\n        <td><span class=\"tcs-risk tcs-risk--high\">High</span></td>\n\n        <td>\n          <strong style=\"color:#ffcc33;\">0 / 10,000</strong><br>\n          <span class=\"tcs-tagline\">Automatic fail</span>\n        </td>\n\n        <td>\n          <span class=\"tcs-issue-pill\">Unverified licence</span>\n          <span class=\"tcs-issue-pill\">Withdrawal caps &amp; fees</span>\n          <span class=\"tcs-issue-pill\">Contradictory support</span>\n          <span class=\"tcs-issue-pill\">Suspicious review signals</span>\n        </td>\n\n        <td>\n          <span class=\"tcs-tag-pill\">NO-LICENCE</span>\n          <span class=\"tcs-tag-pill\">WITHDRAWAL-CAPS</span>\n          <span class=\"tcs-tag-pill\">REVIEW-PATTERN</span>\n        </td>\n\n        <td class=\"tcs-blacklist-evidence-cell\">\n          <a class=\"tcs-btn tcs-btn--secondary\" href=\"/cazinostars-uk-review-blacklisted/\">\n            Read\n          </a>\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n\n      <!-- Royal Reels -->\n      <tr>\n        <td class=\"tcs-blacklist-col-logo\">\n          <img\n            src=\"/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/royalreels-square.webp\"\n            alt=\"Royal Reels logo\"\n            class=\"tcs-blacklist-logo\"\n            loading=\"lazy\">\n        </td>\n\n        <td>\n          <strong style=\"color:#ffdd55;\">Royal Reels</strong><br>\n          <span class=\"tcs-tagline\">Blacklisted \u2022 Avoid depositing</span>\n        </td>\n\n        <td><span class=\"tcs-risk tcs-risk--severe\">Severe</span></td>\n\n        <td>\n          <strong style=\"color:#ffcc33;\">0 / 10,000</strong><br>\n          <span class=\"tcs-tagline\">Automatic fail</span>\n        </td>\n\n        <td>\n          <span class=\"tcs-issue-pill\">Regulator blocking</span>\n          <span class=\"tcs-issue-pill\">Rotating login domains</span>\n          <span class=\"tcs-issue-pill\">Licence unclear</span>\n          <span class=\"tcs-issue-pill\">Withdrawal &amp; KYC complaints</span>\n        </td>\n\n        <td>\n          <span class=\"tcs-tag-pill\">REGULATOR-WARNING</span>\n          <span class=\"tcs-tag-pill\">DOMAIN-HOPPING</span>\n          <span class=\"tcs-tag-pill\">NON-PAYMENT-REPORTS</span>\n        </td>\n\n        <td class=\"tcs-blacklist-evidence-cell\">\n          <a class=\"tcs-btn tcs-btn--secondary\" href=\"/royal-reels-casino-login-warning-review/\">\n            Read\n          </a>\n        </td>\n      </tr>\n    </tbody>\n  </table>\n\n  <p class=\"tcs-text-muted\" style=\"margin:12px 0 0;\">\n    Want safer options instead of a casino blacklist? Start here:\n    <a href=\"/casino-bonus-finder/\" style=\"color:#ffcc33;text-decoration:none;\">AI Bonus Finder</a>\n    \u2022\n    <a href=\"/top-casino-bonuses/\" style=\"color:#ffcc33;text-decoration:none;\">Top Casino Bonuses</a>\n    \u2022\n    <a href=\"/casino-promo-codes/\" style=\"color:#ffcc33;text-decoration:none;\">Casino Promo Codes</a>\n  </p>\n\n</div>\n\n```html\n<!-- DEPTH SECTION: WHY CASINOS GET BLACKLISTED + RISKS + UPDATES + WHAT TO DO -->\n<div class=\"tcs-review-block\" style=\"max-width:960px;margin:0 auto 24px;\">\n  <div class=\"tcs-label-pill\">Why casinos get blacklisted</div>\n  <h2 style=\"margin-top:6px;\">Common reasons a casino ends up on an online casino blacklist</h2>\n\n  <p>\n    Not every negative review is a blacklist event. A casino can have slow support on a busy weekend and still be legitimate. A casino blacklist exists for\n    repeatable, verifiable risk signals that materially increase the chance of financial harm\u2014especially where players may be unable to withdraw winnings,\n    cannot verify who regulates the operator, or face terms that are designed to trap funds. TopCasinoScout\u2019s <strong>online casino blacklist</strong> focuses\n    on issues that are practical, measurable, and difficult to justify as a one-off mistake. If you see a casino listed here, the warning is not based on a\n    single complaint; it is based on an evidence trail that indicates elevated risk.\n  </p>\n\n  <p>\n    The most common trigger for a <strong>casino blacklist</strong> entry is a licensing problem. Some operators display a regulator logo without providing a\n    licence number, licence holder name, or jurisdiction that can be confirmed independently. Others present outdated credentials, recycled licence details,\n    or a \u201clicenced\u201d claim that does not match the domain players are using. When licensing cannot be verified through a credible regulator or a confirmable\n    licence holder trail, player protection becomes unclear: disputes are harder to escalate, and enforcement is less likely. Licensing failures also correlate\n    strongly with other risk patterns such as domain hopping, unclear ownership, and inconsistent terms\u2014so we treat them as high-severity signals.\n  </p>\n\n  <p>\n    The second major category is payout risk. A blacklisted casino often shows friction at the exact moment a player tries to withdraw\u2014sudden \u201cverification\n    requirements\u201d that do not end, repeated document rejections, changing limits or fees after a withdrawal request, or ambiguous discretion clauses that allow\n    the operator to delay cash-outs indefinitely. Some casinos implement extremely restrictive caps or withdrawal fees that make it functionally difficult to\n    access funds, even if a withdrawal is eventually approved. Where credible, repeatable patterns of obstruction exist\u2014especially paired with unclear licensing\u2014\n    the risk profile becomes unacceptable. This is why payout reliability sits at the center of our blacklist criteria.\n  </p>\n\n  <div class=\"tcs-review-block tcs-verdict-box\" style=\"margin:16px 0 18px;\">\n    <div class=\"tcs-label-pill\">Blacklist trigger categories (fast scan)</div>\n    <ul style=\"margin:0; padding-left:18px;\">\n      <li><strong>Licence verification failures:</strong> no confirmable regulator, licence number, or licence holder trail for the operating brand/domain.</li>\n      <li><strong>Withdrawal obstruction:</strong> recurring delays, KYC loops, shifting rules, punitive caps/fees, or disputes that do not resolve.</li>\n      <li><strong>Terms engineered for loss:</strong> predatory clauses, unclear bonus conditions, or \u201cdiscretion\u201d language used to restrict cash-outs.</li>\n      <li><strong>Deception patterns:</strong> misleading marketing, suspicious review behaviour, or inconsistent claims about ownership/licensing.</li>\n      <li><strong>Domain hopping:</strong> rotating mirror sites or numbered \u201clogin\u201d domains that reduce accountability and traceability.</li>\n      <li><strong>Regulator action:</strong> public warnings, enforcement notices, or ISP-blocking orders where applicable.</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"tcs-label-pill\">Risks of playing at blacklisted casinos</div>\n  <h2 style=\"margin-top:6px;\">What can go wrong when you deposit at an unsafe operator</h2>\n\n  <p>\n    Players often land on a blacklist page after a negative experience, but prevention is the best outcome. The risk is not only \u201ca bad experience\u201d; the real\n    problem is that blacklisted casinos tend to fail in ways that directly affect money, identity verification, and dispute resolution. The most obvious risk\n    is delayed or denied payouts: withdrawals can be stalled, reduced, capped, or routed into long verification cycles that never conclude. In higher-severity\n    cases, accounts may be restricted after a win, with the casino citing \u201csecurity\u201d or \u201cresponsible gambling\u201d language without explaining a specific breach.\n    When payouts are the point of failure, it becomes difficult for a player to restore control over their funds.\n  </p>\n\n  <p>\n    Another under-discussed risk is loss of meaningful player protection. If a casino\u2019s licence cannot be verified, there may be no credible regulator to contact,\n    no enforceable dispute pathway, and no clear standards the operator is required to meet. Even where a casino claims a licence, players can be exposed if the\n    stated licence holder cannot be matched to the domain or operator running the product. This is why we treat licensing clarity as foundational: you cannot rely\n    on accountability if you cannot confirm who is accountable. A third risk is terms-based confiscation: vague clauses, high-wagering bonus conditions, low cash-out\n    caps, and discretionary terms can be used to deny withdrawals even when a player believes they have complied.\n  </p>\n\n  <p>\n    Domain rotation adds another layer of risk. Casinos that cycle domains (including numbered \u201clogin\u201d pages) are harder to track, harder to verify, and harder to\n    hold responsible. These patterns can also be used to evade regulator attention, reduce complaint visibility, or push players toward \u201cfresh\u201d domains after negative\n    coverage grows. A final risk is time and identity exposure: repeated KYC demands can lead to sensitive documents being shared with an operator whose legal status,\n    ownership structure, or data handling practices are unclear. In practical terms, if you do not trust an operator with withdrawals, you should not trust them with\n    identity documents either.\n  </p>\n\n  <div class=\"tcs-review-block\" style=\"margin:18px 0 0;\">\n    <div class=\"tcs-label-pill\">How often this casino blacklist is updated</div>\n    <h2 style=\"margin-top:6px;\">When new casinos are added and what \u201cLast updated\u201d means</h2>\n\n    <p>\n      This <strong>online casino blacklist</strong> is updated whenever a new evidence trail reaches a \u201cblacklist threshold\u201d under our framework. That threshold is\n      usually triggered by one of two paths: (1) a hard failure such as a non-verifiable licence claim, a regulator warning, or clear domain-hopping behaviour; or\n      (2) compounded risk signals\u2014multiple, consistent indicators across withdrawals, KYC behaviour, terms, and complaint patterns that materially increase player risk.\n      The \u201cLast updated\u201d label reflects the most recent change to the blacklist page itself (for example, new entries added, risk labels adjusted, or evidence tags updated),\n      not a marketing refresh. If a casino improves and can demonstrate sustained corrective action with verifiable proof, it may be re-evaluated, but removals are not\n      automated and are not influenced by payment.\n    </p>\n\n    <p>\n      A key principle of a credible <strong>casino blacklist</strong> is independence. TopCasinoScout does not accept payment to remove brands from this page.\n      Reconsideration requires documented, verifiable changes\u2014such as transparent licensing clarity, materially improved withdrawal outcomes over time, consistent and fair KYC\n      handling, and a sustained reduction in complaint signals. If evidence improves but remains mixed, we may adjust risk framing, tags, or warnings, but the default stance\n      remains player-first: a casino must earn trust over time, not request it through statements.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"tcs-review-block tcs-verdict-box\" style=\"margin:18px 0 0;\">\n    <div class=\"tcs-label-pill\">If you\u2019ve already deposited</div>\n    <p style=\"margin:0 0 10px;\">\n      If you suspect you\u2019re dealing with an unsafe casino, your goal is to reduce exposure and build an evidence trail. These steps are not legal advice,\n      but they are practical actions players can take to protect themselves.\n    </p>\n\n    <ul style=\"margin:0; padding-left:18px;\">\n      <li><strong>Stop depositing immediately</strong> until you understand the operator\u2019s licence status and withdrawal rules.</li>\n      <li><strong>Document everything</strong>: screenshots of terms, your account status, withdrawal requests, emails, and live chat transcripts.</li>\n      <li><strong>Read the withdrawal and KYC clauses</strong> and note any caps, fees, or \u201cdiscretion\u201d language that can be used to delay payment.</li>\n      <li><strong>Escalate in writing</strong> through support and request a clear reason for any delay, including which clause is being applied.</li>\n      <li><strong>Use payment provider dispute routes</strong> where applicable (card issuer, e-wallet, or bank) if you believe you have been misled or treated unfairly.</li>\n      <li><strong>Check regulator resources</strong> if the casino claims a licence\u2014confirm the licence holder and domain are genuinely covered.</li>\n    </ul>\n\n    <p class=\"tcs-text-muted\" style=\"margin:10px 0 0;\">\n      If you have evidence that a casino should be added to this online casino blacklist, send details via\n      <a href=\"/contact-us/\" style=\"color:#ffcc33;text-decoration:none;\">Contact Us</a>.\n      We review submissions under the same evidence-led framework used for published entries.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"tcs-internal-links\" style=\"margin-top:14px;\">\n    Prefer safer alternatives? Use <a href=\"/casino-bonus-finder/\">AI Bonus Finder</a> \u2022\n    Browse <a href=\"/top-casino-bonuses/\">Top Casino Bonuses</a> \u2022\n    Read <a href=\"/detailed-casino-reviews/\">Casino Reviews</a>\n  </div>\n</div>\n```\n\n\n<!-- EVIDENCE TAGS (SHORT LEGEND) -->\n<div class=\"tcs-review-block\" style=\"max-width:960px;margin:0 auto 24px;\">\n  <div class=\"tcs-label-pill\">Evidence tags (how to read the casino blacklist)</div>\n\n  <p style=\"margin:0 0 12px;\">\n    Evidence tags are the fastest way to interpret our <strong>online casino blacklist</strong>. One tag can be a warning; multiple tags are a pattern.\n    When licence uncertainty overlaps with payout friction or domain switching, the risk profile usually increases sharply.\n  </p>\n\n  <ul style=\"margin:0; padding-left:18px;\">\n    <li><strong>NO-LICENCE</strong> \u2014 licensing claim could not be verified through a regulator, licence holder, or confirmable credential trail.</li>\n    <li><strong>REGULATOR-WARNING</strong> \u2014 public notice, enforcement action, or blocking order that materially increases risk.</li>\n    <li><strong>DOMAIN-HOPPING</strong> \u2014 rotating mirror domains or numbered \u201clogin\u201d pages that reduce traceability and accountability.</li>\n    <li><strong>WITHDRAWAL-CAPS</strong> \u2014 unusually strict caps, extra fees, or cashout restrictions that limit player access to winnings.</li>\n    <li><strong>NON-PAYMENT-REPORTS</strong> \u2014 consistent allegations of withheld funds, prolonged delays, or dispute loops that do not resolve.</li>\n    <li><strong>REVIEW-PATTERN</strong> \u2014 suspicious review signals (uniform language, promotional tone, or inconsistencies) that reduce